        'sort_order' => 3974,
        'context' => 'A defined response procedure that is to be followed by a trained response team when triaging incidents reduces response times, suboptimal decision making, and enables an organization to quickly contain the potential damage that can be caused by a security incident.',
    ],
    [
        'framework_slug' => 'ofdss',
        'code' => 'Maintain segmented networks',
        'title' => 'Maintain segmented networks',
        'description' => 'Maintain segmented networks',
        'principle_id' => 'Domain 10',
        'principle_name' => 'Network Security',
        'variants' => [],
        'source' => 'vanta',
        'source_file' => 'resources/frameworks/vanta/raw/ofdss.json',
        'sort_order' => 3975,
        'context' => 'The opposite of a flat network is a segmented network, and it allows an organization to granularly separate assets with different levels of sensitivity and usage from exposure to each other, and to other networks (e.g. the WWW).
An asset with no reason for having access to the internet (e.g. a database containing sensitive data that only interacts with internal services), can live inside a private segmented network, while an asset that have a reason for being visible to the open internet (e.g. a reverse proxy / load balancer) can live inside a network that is open to the web. Both of these assets should not exist in the same subnetwork because their sensitivity, purpose, and network access needs are different.',
    ],
    [
        'framework_slug' => 'ofdss',
